<!-- COMPARISON -->
<section id="comparison">
  <div class="container">

    <div class="section-header fade-in">
      <span class="section-label">Traditional vs. Spine</span>
      <div class="section-divider"></div>
      <h2>What Changes When Governance Is Architectural</h2>
      <p>Not theoretical improvements. Operational differences you can verify today.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare-table-wrap fade-in">

      <div class="compare-table-header">
        <div class="compare-th aspect">Aspect</div>
        <div class="compare-th traditional">Traditional Approach</div>
        <div class="compare-th purebrain">PureBrain Governance Spine</div>
      </div>

      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Violation detection</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">Quarterly audit cycle &mdash; violations accumulate for months before review</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">Pre-execution gate fires before the action &mdash; violation never executes</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Rule enforcement</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">Policy documents in English. Relies on agents reading and choosing to comply.</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">Constitutional constraints in the operating layer. Bypassing requires breaking the system.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Domain violations</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">Discovered in post-incident review, often after damage is done</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">Flagged at routing gate immediately, escalated to Primary before execution proceeds</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Constitutional amendment</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">Senior leadership decision &mdash; often undocumented, no audit trail</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">Multi-agent consensus required, 60% threshold, documented rationale in git</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Oversight independence</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">Internal audit reports to the same leadership it audits &mdash; structural capture risk</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">Security, QA, integration audit functions structurally isolated with restricted scope mandates</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Configuration audit trail</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">Policy documents updated in shared drives &mdash; version history unreliable or absent</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">Every configuration change is a git commit with timestamp, attribution, and full diff</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Scale as ops grow</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">More agents means more compliance burden and more humans required to review</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">More agents means more cross-checks &mdash; governance strengthens as the system scales</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-tr">
        <div class="compare-td aspect">Knowledge before action</div>
        <div class="compare-td traditional td-bad">No mechanism prevents acting on stale data &mdash; relies on agent discipline</div>
        <div class="compare-td purebrain td-good">Memory-first protocol mandatory pre-execution &mdash; enforced, not suggested</div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="shield-section fade-in">
      <div>
        <svg width="72" height="72" viewBox="0 0 72 72" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <path d="M36 6L10 16V34C10 50 21 63 36 68C51 63 62 50 62 34V16L36 6Z" fill="rgba(42,147,193,0.1)" stroke="#2a93c1" stroke-width="2"/>
          <circle cx="36" cy="35" r="10" fill="none" stroke="#2a93c1" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <path d="M31 35L34.5 38.5L41.5 31.5" stroke="#2a93c1" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          <circle cx="36" cy="18" r="3" fill="rgba(241,66,11,0.6)" stroke="#f1420b" stroke-width="1"/>
          <circle cx="50" cy="27" r="2.5" fill="rgba(42,147,193,0.5)" stroke="#2a93c1" stroke-width="1"/>
          <circle cx="22" cy="27" r="2.5" fill="rgba(42,147,193,0.5)" stroke="#2a93c1" stroke-width="1"/>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div class="shield-text">
        <h3>The Governance Inversion</h3>
        <p>
          Traditional compliance asks: &ldquo;Did anyone break the rules?&rdquo; and checks quarterly.
          <strong>The Governance Spine asks: &ldquo;Can the rules even be broken?&rdquo; and enforces continuously.</strong>
          The answer is architectural, not procedural. Rules that fire pre-execution cannot be violated through omission or bad judgment. They can only be violated by deliberately dismantling the system &mdash; which itself creates an audit record.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <img src="images/governance-network.png" alt="30+ AI agents in a governed constellation network with central conductor node" class="section-image fade-in" loading="lazy" style="margin-top:48px" />

  </div>
</section>

